<dl id="n10109d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n10" href="#n10109d">N10 (VI.B.16)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n10all.htm#n10109d"> 109(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> blew luck to <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n10109d"><li>FW 428.13 </li><li><a href="../../flex/pD/lexpD.htm#n10109d">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/pD/l39pD.htm#n10109d">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n10109d">MS BL 47482b-43v</ms> </li><li>JJA 57:088 <a name="pA3d" href="../../ff/fdra/pda.htm#pD3d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/p/pd3d.htm#n10109d">Draft: III&sect;1D.3</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><b>May Day Festivities and Traditions / Echoes of Pagan Worship</b> May Eve and May Day were once the great feasts of Baal, the sun-god, when his fires were lit on the hillsides and children and cattle were passed through them for purification.<font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> Lucky South Wind. The very wind on May Morn might be used for prophesying. As a rule, a south wind <mark>blew luck</mark> to Ireland and the Irish, a north wind meant victory to their enemies. <small> <a name="II30apr24" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#II30apr24"><cite title="source">Irish Independent</cite></a> (30 April 1924) 6/5</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
